sect1.para:
A strong working alliance between the mental health professional and the client is necessary when assessing for mental health problems and working toward achieving correct diagnosis, as well as treatment goals. This is especially true when assessing for trauma-related disorders because the phenotype of PTSD is often confusing and difficult to identify, as it can be masked or exacerbated by other disorders such as traumatic brain injury, depression, substance use, or anxiety disorder. In addition, people may not realize they have PTSD because they view their symptoms as a sign that they are having difficulty coping (i. e., “there’s something wrong with me”) (Ellis & Zaretsky,
         2018
      ).

While interviews are the first step in forming a diagnosis, it is also essential to let the client actively participate in the evaluation process. Information from cognitive and mood assessments can inform case conceptualization and guide treatment planning if the client has given their best effort in responding and is forthcoming when completing measures. Self-report measures, where the client rates their distress levels and endorses the presence and magnitude of various symptoms, are psychology’s most widely used measurement tools (Haeffel & Howard,
         2010
      ). Indeed, there are a variety of trauma and stressor-related disorder self-report measures that can be used to identify the symptoms, rate their onset and severity, as well as monitor for any change in diagnosis throughout treatment. Some self-report measures can help the clinician and client monitor whether the treatment is effective.
